WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.994 --> 00:00:04.473
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:34.790 --> 00:00:37.772
ANNIE WILKES: I am your
number one fan, I sure am.

00:00:37.772 --> 00:00:40.860
And trust me, there
ain't no number two.

00:00:40.860 --> 00:00:44.337
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:01:06.390 --> 00:01:07.140
ALAN SEALES: Whoo!

00:01:07.140 --> 00:01:07.640
All right.

00:01:07.640 --> 00:01:09.310
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:09.310 --> 00:01:10.970
So it would probably
be easiest here

00:01:10.970 --> 00:01:12.770
if you-- let's start with
you, Michael, on the end.

00:01:12.770 --> 00:01:14.920
Just go down the line here
and introduce yourselves.

00:01:14.920 --> 00:01:15.445
MARK KAUFMAN: Mark Kaufman.

00:01:15.445 --> 00:01:16.040
ALAN SEALES: Oh, Mark.

00:01:16.040 --> 00:01:16.540
Sorry.

00:01:16.540 --> 00:01:18.150
MARK KAUFMAN: No-- producer.

00:01:18.150 --> 00:01:20.270
MICHAEL FRIEDMAN: Michael
Friedman, composer.

00:01:20.270 --> 00:01:22.420
LEON ADDISON BROWN: Leon
Addison Brown, actor.

00:01:22.420 --> 00:01:24.190
LAURIE METCALF: Laurie
Metcalf, act-- or.

00:01:24.190 --> 00:01:25.207
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:25.207 --> 00:01:26.290
WILL FREARS: Are you sure?

00:01:26.290 --> 00:01:28.482
LAURIE METCALF: Yes, I am sure.

00:01:28.482 --> 00:01:29.940
WILL FREARS: Will
Frears, director.

00:01:29.940 --> 00:01:31.710
ALAN SEALES: Laurie, you were
covering your ears during that.

00:01:31.710 --> 00:01:32.060
Is that--

00:01:32.060 --> 00:01:34.476
LAURIE METCALF: I had to be
tapped to walk up on the stage

00:01:34.476 --> 00:01:37.860
because I was bent over like
that with my ears covered.

00:01:37.860 --> 00:01:40.130
Because I can't
watch any of that.

00:01:40.130 --> 00:01:42.580
Because it's very
distressing to me.

00:01:42.580 --> 00:01:44.330
ALAN SEALES: Does it
scare you to watch it

00:01:44.330 --> 00:01:45.829
as much as it scares
the rest of us?

00:01:45.829 --> 00:01:49.080
LAURIE METCALF:
No, it's not scary.

00:01:49.080 --> 00:01:50.432
I can't watch myself--

00:01:50.432 --> 00:01:51.390
ALAN SEALES: Oh, right.

00:01:51.390 --> 00:01:52.931
LAURIE METCALF:
--because in my head,

00:01:52.931 --> 00:01:55.530
it looks completely different
than what that just is.

00:01:55.530 --> 00:01:58.439
So I can't see it.

00:01:58.439 --> 00:01:59.480
ALAN SEALES: Interesting.

00:01:59.480 --> 00:02:01.780
So you've had a very
versatile career.

00:02:01.780 --> 00:02:03.579
I mean, you've been
in many movies, lots

00:02:03.579 --> 00:02:05.370
of television, "Roseanne,"
of course, where

00:02:05.370 --> 00:02:08.491
you won three Emmy awards.

00:02:08.491 --> 00:02:09.949
Numerous theater
productions, where

00:02:09.949 --> 00:02:11.610
you got two Tony nominations.

00:02:11.610 --> 00:02:14.440
And you're even the voice of
Andy's mom in the "Toy Story"

00:02:14.440 --> 00:02:18.720
movies, which I was
very happy to discover.

00:02:18.720 --> 00:02:21.295
Is there any particular genre
that you like more than others?

00:02:21.295 --> 00:02:22.560
LAURIE METCALF: Oh,
yeah, theater, by far.

00:02:22.560 --> 00:02:22.830
ALAN SEALES: Really?

00:02:22.830 --> 00:02:22.990
LAURIE METCALF: Yeah.

00:02:22.990 --> 00:02:24.910
Maybe it's because I
came up in theater,

00:02:24.910 --> 00:02:27.340
with Steppenwolf
Theatre in Chicago,

00:02:27.340 --> 00:02:30.290
and we're in our 40th
season, I think, now.

00:02:30.290 --> 00:02:33.150
And so I started
there, and that's

00:02:33.150 --> 00:02:37.570
where I learned-- I like the
instant gratification of being

00:02:37.570 --> 00:02:40.270
in front of a live audience.

00:02:40.270 --> 00:02:42.570
And I like the rehearsal
process very much.

00:02:42.570 --> 00:02:45.520
I like the three, four weeks
spent in a rehearsal room

00:02:45.520 --> 00:02:47.850
really hammering out things.

00:02:47.850 --> 00:02:49.160
And I like the run of the show.

00:02:49.160 --> 00:02:51.440
It's all really
different skill sets,

00:02:51.440 --> 00:02:54.820
but I much prefer theater.

00:02:54.820 --> 00:02:57.445
ALAN SEALES: Wow, so you've been
through the rehearsal process.

00:02:57.445 --> 00:03:00.990
So with movies, I don't imagine
you rehearse the whole thing

00:03:00.990 --> 00:03:01.629
all at once.

00:03:01.629 --> 00:03:02.420
LAURIE METCALF: No.

00:03:02.420 --> 00:03:03.150
ALAN SEALES: So you rehearse.

00:03:03.150 --> 00:03:04.640
You go in, and you're like,
oh, here are my lines.

00:03:04.640 --> 00:03:06.540
You've usually got them
in your back pocket.

00:03:06.540 --> 00:03:06.850
LAURIE METCALF: Exactly.

00:03:06.850 --> 00:03:07.560
ALAN SEALES: Right.

00:03:07.560 --> 00:03:08.220
And you rehearse it.

00:03:08.220 --> 00:03:10.553
LAURIE METCALF: You do it out
of order, out of sequence.

00:03:10.553 --> 00:03:13.710
You're shooting the very last
scene of the movie first.

00:03:13.710 --> 00:03:16.650
ALAN SEALES: So is that a
challenge for a show like

00:03:16.650 --> 00:03:20.240
"Misery," where you're on stage
pretty much 90% of the time,

00:03:20.240 --> 00:03:20.740
I would say?

00:03:20.740 --> 00:03:22.948
LAURIE METCALF: Yes, we get
on the "Misery-go-round,"

00:03:22.948 --> 00:03:25.550
and we don't get off
for an hour and a half.

00:03:25.550 --> 00:03:27.244
ALAN SEALES: A literal go-round.

00:03:27.244 --> 00:03:28.660
Yeah, I want to
come back to that.

00:03:28.660 --> 00:03:30.990
The set is phenomenal.

00:03:30.990 --> 00:03:35.050
But approaching the character of
Annie Wilkes, your crazy number

00:03:35.050 --> 00:03:39.980
one fan obsession person,
I mean, she's nuts.

00:03:39.980 --> 00:03:42.016
Do you have any personal
sympathy for her?

00:03:42.016 --> 00:03:43.140
LAURIE METCALF: Yeah, I do.

00:03:43.140 --> 00:03:44.050
I have a lot of sympathy.

00:03:44.050 --> 00:03:45.300
That's what attracted
me to the part.

00:03:45.300 --> 00:03:47.780
Because I was looking for-- we
were just talking about it--

00:03:47.780 --> 00:03:50.400
the heart of the character,
because there has to be.

00:03:50.400 --> 00:03:52.970
It can't just be
labeled a "monster."

00:03:52.970 --> 00:03:57.270
And so there are very
few tiny, tiny hints

00:03:57.270 --> 00:04:00.510
in the script of maybe the
way that she was brought up,

00:04:00.510 --> 00:04:03.070
maybe her relationship
to her mother,

00:04:03.070 --> 00:04:06.720
her relationship to her
miserable stepfather,

00:04:06.720 --> 00:04:11.290
as she just fleetingly mentions.

00:04:11.290 --> 00:04:15.980
The fact that she deals
with Bruce's character

00:04:15.980 --> 00:04:19.000
in a certain way, everything
is very black and white.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:21.750
There's a scene
where she makes him--

00:04:21.750 --> 00:04:23.950
it's kind of like washing
his mouth out with soap

00:04:23.950 --> 00:04:25.380
and drink this water.

00:04:25.380 --> 00:04:30.220
But to me, it just always was
about how she was brought up.

00:04:30.220 --> 00:04:38.890
And so that she wasn't born
this person that is abusive.

00:04:38.890 --> 00:04:43.730
And there's a back history
that's hinted at that.

00:04:43.730 --> 00:04:47.820
When you see it,
hopefully, you forgive

00:04:47.820 --> 00:04:50.257
her a lot of her craziness.

00:04:50.257 --> 00:04:51.840
ALAN SEALES: Yeah,
it was weird for me

00:04:51.840 --> 00:04:54.360
to watch because at
first-- I'm going

00:04:54.360 --> 00:04:56.500
to try to talk without
giving away any spoilers.

00:04:56.500 --> 00:04:59.075
Because you guys have
to go see the show.

00:04:59.075 --> 00:04:59.950
At first, I thought--

00:04:59.950 --> 00:05:00.640
LAURIE METCALF:
But don't everybody

00:05:00.640 --> 00:05:03.890
know-- doesn't most-- what's the
majority of people that know,

00:05:03.890 --> 00:05:05.390
I mean, what happens?

00:05:05.390 --> 00:05:08.370
ALAN SEALES: Who's seen
the movie or read the book?

00:05:08.370 --> 00:05:09.785
OK, I guess that
is the majority.

00:05:09.785 --> 00:05:11.335
LAURIE METCALF: Most.

00:05:11.335 --> 00:05:13.460
ALAN SEALES: I had not seen
either-- seen the movie

00:05:13.460 --> 00:05:15.990
or read the book-- so I
went in completely fresh.

00:05:15.990 --> 00:05:17.330
And--

00:05:17.330 --> 00:05:20.266
LAURIE METCALF: That's
got to be disturbing.

00:05:20.266 --> 00:05:21.682
ALAN SEALES: Yes,
that's why I was

00:05:21.682 --> 00:05:24.340
so excited to talk to you
guys, because I'm still

00:05:24.340 --> 00:05:26.614
disturbed for many reasons.

00:05:26.614 --> 00:05:28.530
And Leon, we'll get to
your scene in a second.

00:05:28.530 --> 00:05:31.180
God, it scared the
shit out of me.

00:05:31.180 --> 00:05:32.350
Excuse me, Spencer.

00:05:35.050 --> 00:05:37.145
Yeah, so your character
gets so manic.

00:05:37.145 --> 00:05:42.330
And at first, I was very
sympathetic with her.

00:05:42.330 --> 00:05:45.750
And I was like, oh,
OK, she means well.

00:05:45.750 --> 00:05:46.940
She's very, very nice.

00:05:46.940 --> 00:05:50.027
And then it's just like,
well, that escalated quickly.

00:05:50.027 --> 00:05:52.110
Again, I don't know want
to give away the spoilers

00:05:52.110 --> 00:05:53.360
for those who haven't seen it.

00:05:53.360 --> 00:05:56.940
But they're like
disfiguration, right?

00:05:56.940 --> 00:05:58.140
That's not a spoiler.

00:05:58.140 --> 00:06:00.440
You've got to go see it.

00:06:00.440 --> 00:06:04.705
So how did you
approach this from sort

00:06:04.705 --> 00:06:07.140
of a character leveling,
emotional leveling perspective?

00:06:07.140 --> 00:06:08.120
LAURIE METCALF: Yeah,
you do have to plot.

00:06:08.120 --> 00:06:09.230
It has to ramp up.

00:06:09.230 --> 00:06:12.240
You can't just go full--

00:06:12.240 --> 00:06:13.240
ALAN SEALES: Full crazy?

00:06:13.240 --> 00:06:14.698
LAURIE METCALF:
Full crazy-- right,

00:06:14.698 --> 00:06:17.770
right-- right out of the gate.

00:06:17.770 --> 00:06:22.080
There are some entry level
drugs that get to the--

00:06:22.080 --> 00:06:28.880
but the mania, I think,
comes from her out

00:06:28.880 --> 00:06:33.430
of proportion fandom for
this particular writer.

00:06:33.430 --> 00:06:38.160
And so the times where she
is rewarded with something--

00:06:38.160 --> 00:06:42.860
hearing that he's got
another book coming out, or--

00:06:42.860 --> 00:06:45.630
ALAN SEALES: Forcing
it to happen?

00:06:45.630 --> 00:06:48.280
LAURIE METCALF: And so
those are the times where

00:06:48.280 --> 00:06:51.020
she spikes up in the mania.

00:06:51.020 --> 00:06:57.070
And another time is when
he's been doing some writing.

00:06:57.070 --> 00:07:00.220
And he has said that her
favorite character, Misery

00:07:00.220 --> 00:07:02.950
Chastain, now comes
from nobility, which she

00:07:02.950 --> 00:07:04.280
knew all the time [INAUDIBLE].

00:07:04.280 --> 00:07:07.180
And then there's another
spike of rolling around

00:07:07.180 --> 00:07:10.260
on the bed like a crazy person.

00:07:10.260 --> 00:07:15.030
So those are the
fun mania moments.

00:07:15.030 --> 00:07:18.599
And then there are others
that are not so fun for him.

00:07:18.599 --> 00:07:19.390
ALAN SEALES: Right.

00:07:19.390 --> 00:07:22.770
So working with
director Will Frears,

00:07:22.770 --> 00:07:25.060
how much of the
character of Annie

00:07:25.060 --> 00:07:28.170
did you bring to
the table combined

00:07:28.170 --> 00:07:29.410
with what Laurie brought?

00:07:29.410 --> 00:07:31.000
WILL FREARS: I mean,
I don't think--

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:32.550
I like to think we
sort of-- I mean,

00:07:32.550 --> 00:07:34.633
mostly I listen to Laurie
because she's brilliant,

00:07:34.633 --> 00:07:37.190
and I try not to get in her way.

00:07:37.190 --> 00:07:38.070
We talk a lot.

00:07:38.070 --> 00:07:40.330
I mean, as we were
getting started,

00:07:40.330 --> 00:07:44.370
we would spend hours
together talking about it,

00:07:44.370 --> 00:07:47.150
talking where we agreed,
where we disagreed,

00:07:47.150 --> 00:07:48.010
where we saw things.

00:07:48.010 --> 00:07:50.320
And one of the great
pleasures of the whole thing

00:07:50.320 --> 00:07:56.550
is that it's been astonishing
to watch Laurie take what

00:07:56.550 --> 00:07:59.710
is a sort of iconic figure
in a particular thing

00:07:59.710 --> 00:08:03.010
and sort of reinvent it
entirely as she sees her,

00:08:03.010 --> 00:08:05.886
and to find this incredible
kind of sympathy.

00:08:05.886 --> 00:08:07.510
I think the thing we
agreed on, always,

00:08:07.510 --> 00:08:09.301
was that she couldn't
be a monster, though.

00:08:09.301 --> 00:08:13.220
We always felt that we had
to look for her humanity

00:08:13.220 --> 00:08:17.200
and that everything she did, we
both, right from the beginning,

00:08:17.200 --> 00:08:19.360
forgave for, and
tried to understand.

00:08:19.360 --> 00:08:22.710
And then from there, really, I
think it's been that I've felt

00:08:22.710 --> 00:08:26.440
like, if I'm lucky enough
to have Laurie like that,

00:08:26.440 --> 00:08:30.460
don't get into-- I mean, suggest
and nudge but don't-- to just

00:08:30.460 --> 00:08:34.049
try and see what she's doing
and help her illuminate that,

00:08:34.049 --> 00:08:38.350
but to very much give her her
head and see where she takes

00:08:38.350 --> 00:08:38.851
it.

00:08:38.851 --> 00:08:41.266
It's thrilling, and every time
I go back and see the show,

00:08:41.266 --> 00:08:42.696
I'm like, oh, that's a new--

00:08:42.696 --> 00:08:43.093
ALAN SEALES: [CHUCKLES]

00:08:43.093 --> 00:08:44.426
WILL FREARS: --oh, she's clever.

00:08:44.426 --> 00:08:45.340
That's very smart.

00:08:45.340 --> 00:08:45.760
ALAN SEALES: Right.

00:08:45.760 --> 00:08:47.718
WILL FREARS: It's really
exciting to come back.

00:08:47.718 --> 00:08:50.704
I've become such a fan that
I go back as Annie Wilkes.

00:08:50.704 --> 00:08:53.120
ALAN SEALES: Is that unusual
to be a fan of your own show?

00:08:53.120 --> 00:08:54.110
WILL FREARS: I'm not
a fan of my show.

00:08:54.110 --> 00:08:54.943
I'm a fan of Laurie.

00:08:54.943 --> 00:08:58.230
They're very-- I'm a fan
of everyone else in it.

00:08:58.230 --> 00:09:00.280
I'm not at all a fan--
I sit there and cringe

00:09:00.280 --> 00:09:02.140
for my own work.

00:09:02.140 --> 00:09:03.640
And then I think,
oh, they're smart.

00:09:03.640 --> 00:09:05.000
Thanks for rescuing me again.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:07.870
No, part of the
pleasure for this thing

00:09:07.870 --> 00:09:10.630
is this is-- because I
haven't had a show on Broadway

00:09:10.630 --> 00:09:13.000
before-- to watch a show
run this long, for me,

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:13.710
is a real treat.

00:09:13.710 --> 00:09:17.650
And to see Bruce and Laurie
and Leon find new things,

00:09:17.650 --> 00:09:20.370
change things, add nuance,
add meaning, add texture,

00:09:20.370 --> 00:09:23.910
so that every time I go back,
it's things they've found.

00:09:23.910 --> 00:09:26.470
It's not at all things that
I have been like, oh, god,

00:09:26.470 --> 00:09:27.803
that was such a good idea by me.

00:09:27.803 --> 00:09:31.340
It's watching them investigate
another part of the play,

00:09:31.340 --> 00:09:33.069
find a new beat,
find a different way

00:09:33.069 --> 00:09:33.860
of doing something.

00:09:33.860 --> 00:09:36.340
It's just a kind
of-- it's a treat.

00:09:36.340 --> 00:09:38.954
Because, as Laurie said at the
beginning, it sort of lives.

00:09:38.954 --> 00:09:40.370
It's a living
organism, and so you

00:09:40.370 --> 00:09:42.410
get to go back and visit it.

00:09:42.410 --> 00:09:44.374
But it's not at all as
a fan-- not a fan of me

00:09:44.374 --> 00:09:46.040
ALAN SEALES: Yeah,
which is, personally,

00:09:46.040 --> 00:09:48.320
why I enjoy doing
theater over film.

00:09:48.320 --> 00:09:51.560
Because even though up to
rehearsals, the script changes,

00:09:51.560 --> 00:09:52.870
and whatnot, you lock it in.

00:09:52.870 --> 00:09:55.720
But even though it's locked, you
can say the exact same things

00:09:55.720 --> 00:09:59.652
every night and have them mean
completely different things.

00:09:59.652 --> 00:10:00.860
They have different subtexts.

00:10:00.860 --> 00:10:04.930
So Will, you've been
involved with movies,

00:10:04.930 --> 00:10:08.084
both in front of the camera
and behind the camera.

00:10:08.084 --> 00:10:10.500
WILL FREARS: Only once in
front, and I was playing myself.

00:10:10.500 --> 00:10:11.864
So it wasn't huge.

00:10:11.864 --> 00:10:14.030
It was interesting that
somebody called me and said,

00:10:14.030 --> 00:10:15.410
will you come play
a theater director?

00:10:15.410 --> 00:10:16.130
And I was like, yeah.

00:10:16.130 --> 00:10:16.580
OK.

00:10:16.580 --> 00:10:17.788
ALAN SEALES: All right, easy.

00:10:17.788 --> 00:10:19.470
And action.

00:10:19.470 --> 00:10:21.350
So you were an actor
and writer and whatnot,

00:10:21.350 --> 00:10:23.433
but you've been doing a
lot of directing recently.

00:10:23.433 --> 00:10:25.760
How did you get
involved with "Misery"?

00:10:25.760 --> 00:10:28.840
WILL FREARS: I got a
call from my agent.

00:10:28.840 --> 00:10:32.052
It's a sort of really-- it's
the most traditional story.

00:10:32.052 --> 00:10:33.510
I got a call from
my agent, saying,

00:10:33.510 --> 00:10:35.907
what are you doing next week?

00:10:35.907 --> 00:10:38.490
And I said, well, I'm quite busy
next week, because on Sunday,

00:10:38.490 --> 00:10:41.120
my wife is going into hospital
and we're-- she's going to have

00:10:41.120 --> 00:10:41.797
a baby.

00:10:41.797 --> 00:10:42.880
ALAN SEALES: Oh, congrats.

00:10:42.880 --> 00:10:43.838
WILL FREARS: Thank you.

00:10:43.838 --> 00:10:45.703
And he said, OK, but
later in the week.

00:10:45.703 --> 00:10:46.699
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:46.699 --> 00:10:48.240
ALAN SEALES: I
[INAUDIBLE] and sleep.

00:10:48.240 --> 00:10:49.073
WILL FREARS: Uh-huh.

00:10:49.073 --> 00:10:51.270
And I said, well, could
we do it next week?

00:10:51.270 --> 00:10:53.520
And he said that
there had been a call,

00:10:53.520 --> 00:10:57.340
and could I go and
meet about "Misery."

00:10:57.340 --> 00:11:00.620
And so I sat in the
hospital room at NYU

00:11:00.620 --> 00:11:02.890
with my two-day-old
daughter, and I'm just

00:11:02.890 --> 00:11:06.990
reading this book-- trying
to reconcile becoming

00:11:06.990 --> 00:11:09.170
a father with this horror.

00:11:09.170 --> 00:11:10.490
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:10.490 --> 00:11:14.150
ALAN SEALES: Please don't
make it turn out like this.

00:11:14.150 --> 00:11:18.300
WILL FREARS: And I took
meetings with everyone.

00:11:18.300 --> 00:11:20.410
And I took meetings with Mark.

00:11:20.410 --> 00:11:22.800
Mark and I had breakfast at
the Brooklyn Diner, I think,

00:11:22.800 --> 00:11:24.000
was where we first sat down.

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:26.150
MARK KAUFMAN: That was
our first meal, yeah.

00:11:26.150 --> 00:11:29.500
WILL FREARS: And I started
working with Bill Goldman,

00:11:29.500 --> 00:11:33.480
And that was how it started,
and we sort of clicked.

00:11:33.480 --> 00:11:39.240
And the original draft of the
script was all in projections.

00:11:39.240 --> 00:11:41.780
It was all done with
like, she does a thing,

00:11:41.780 --> 00:11:46.040
and then an image would
flash on the screen.

00:11:46.040 --> 00:11:47.931
And I said to Bill,
I was like, look,

00:11:47.931 --> 00:11:49.680
you don't have to give
me this job at all.

00:11:49.680 --> 00:11:51.804
But if you don't do these
things for real on stage,

00:11:51.804 --> 00:11:53.890
the audience is
going to hate you.

00:11:53.890 --> 00:11:56.680
There's quite some significant
acts of violence in the play,

00:11:56.680 --> 00:11:58.560
and they were all
done back there.

00:11:58.560 --> 00:12:00.050
And I was like, look, if
you don't actually do the--

00:12:00.050 --> 00:12:01.100
ALAN SEALES: Like a
silhouette, or something?

00:12:01.100 --> 00:12:02.433
WILL FREARS: No, like a picture.

00:12:02.433 --> 00:12:03.780
Like in still-- like a film.

00:12:03.780 --> 00:12:06.680
And I was, like, you have to
do the thing-- for those of you

00:12:06.680 --> 00:12:10.410
who know what the thing
is, you have to do that,

00:12:10.410 --> 00:12:12.200
or they'll hate you for it.

00:12:12.200 --> 00:12:14.227
And he went, can
you really do that?

00:12:14.227 --> 00:12:14.935
And I said, yeah.

00:12:14.935 --> 00:12:17.194
And he said, fuck.

00:12:17.194 --> 00:12:18.360
ALAN SEALES: Sorry, Spencer.

00:12:18.360 --> 00:12:22.970
WILL FREARS: Sorry--
or not sorry.

00:12:22.970 --> 00:12:24.470
And that was how
we started working.

00:12:24.470 --> 00:12:25.970
And so the first
thing we did was we

00:12:25.970 --> 00:12:28.920
took out all these projections
and went on from there.

00:12:28.920 --> 00:12:31.880
And that was five years ago.

00:12:31.880 --> 00:12:32.880
ALAN SEALES: Five years?

00:12:32.880 --> 00:12:33.380
Wow.

00:12:33.380 --> 00:12:34.593
OK.

00:12:34.593 --> 00:12:35.676
WILL FREARS: Two children.

00:12:35.676 --> 00:12:38.410
ALAN SEALES: So Mark,
I guess five years ago,

00:12:38.410 --> 00:12:40.330
you started this.

00:12:40.330 --> 00:12:43.580
Warner Brothers, big studio--
big studio execs sitting here,

00:12:43.580 --> 00:12:44.790
right?

00:12:44.790 --> 00:12:46.890
Yes, that's what I
tell myself, and that's

00:12:46.890 --> 00:12:48.260
what you should tell yourself.

00:12:48.260 --> 00:12:50.629
And so you got involved.

00:12:50.629 --> 00:12:52.670
We were talking a little
bit at lunch about this.

00:12:52.670 --> 00:12:56.530
But I want to go into
a little bit more.

00:12:56.530 --> 00:12:58.630
This is the first
show on Broadway

00:12:58.630 --> 00:13:01.460
I've seen where I've realized
that a big movie studioesque

00:13:01.460 --> 00:13:03.480
kind of organization
owned the rights

00:13:03.480 --> 00:13:06.550
and then put it on stage.

00:13:06.550 --> 00:13:08.760
So how did Warner
Brothers, in general,

00:13:08.760 --> 00:13:11.390
even get to own the
rights in the first place?

00:13:11.390 --> 00:13:13.750
MICHAEL FRIEDMAN: Well, I'll
go with the quick answers.

00:13:13.750 --> 00:13:15.530
First of all, we're sort of
following in the footsteps

00:13:15.530 --> 00:13:16.270
of other studios.

00:13:16.270 --> 00:13:18.180
Disney, obviously,
started paving the way

00:13:18.180 --> 00:13:19.690
with their shows.

00:13:19.690 --> 00:13:22.340
And Universal's
involved in "Wicked."

00:13:22.340 --> 00:13:24.980
But I actually didn't
put it into development.

00:13:24.980 --> 00:13:27.110
I came after it had already
been in development.

00:13:27.110 --> 00:13:29.050
So I was the next
regime who decides,

00:13:29.050 --> 00:13:32.350
do things move forward or
do things sort of stop?

00:13:32.350 --> 00:13:35.230
And one of the things--
my very first meeting

00:13:35.230 --> 00:13:37.089
when I started the
studio was "Misery"

00:13:37.089 --> 00:13:39.380
is in development with Bill
Goldman, who I had actually

00:13:39.380 --> 00:13:42.750
hired for another project,
as a movie studio executive,

00:13:42.750 --> 00:13:43.260
to write.

00:13:43.260 --> 00:13:45.110
So we had a shorthand.

00:13:45.110 --> 00:13:48.280
And I met Will, as he said,
at the Brooklyn Diner.

00:13:48.280 --> 00:13:50.630
And there was something
about "Misery"

00:13:50.630 --> 00:13:52.820
that I just really loved.

00:13:52.820 --> 00:13:55.340
And I always felt-- part
of what I was brought on

00:13:55.340 --> 00:13:57.110
to do when I was
hired at the studio

00:13:57.110 --> 00:14:00.920
was to go through the catalog
and see which movie or TV

00:14:00.920 --> 00:14:04.880
projects or cartoons felt
like they belonged on stage.

00:14:04.880 --> 00:14:07.440
And "Misery" felt like
such a natural to me.

00:14:07.440 --> 00:14:10.420
And I had also this
very interesting story

00:14:10.420 --> 00:14:11.230
with Bill Goldman.

00:14:11.230 --> 00:14:13.800
I was in graduate
school, and Bill Goldman

00:14:13.800 --> 00:14:16.050
came to speak to
us about "Misery."

00:14:16.050 --> 00:14:19.150
So I had this weird
connection from almost--

00:14:19.150 --> 00:14:22.080
it had to be 20-something
years earlier.

00:14:22.080 --> 00:14:25.850
And I also had this weird
connection to-- when I grew up,

00:14:25.850 --> 00:14:27.670
there was a play
called "Deathtrap"

00:14:27.670 --> 00:14:28.890
that I was obsessed with.

00:14:28.890 --> 00:14:31.050
And I saw it three, four times.

00:14:31.050 --> 00:14:33.037
And I always wanted to
do that on Broadway.

00:14:33.037 --> 00:14:34.620
And they don't do
those shows anymore.

00:14:34.620 --> 00:14:38.020
So this sort of ticked three
or four different boxes.

00:14:38.020 --> 00:14:39.770
I wanted to work with Bill.

00:14:39.770 --> 00:14:41.680
I was really taken by Will.

00:14:41.680 --> 00:14:42.779
I loved the property.

00:14:42.779 --> 00:14:44.320
I'd seen the movie
and read the book.

00:14:44.320 --> 00:14:48.130
And it just felt like a natural
to push forward, and we did.

00:14:48.130 --> 00:14:49.920
ALAN SEALES: You
said, Bill Goldman.

00:14:49.920 --> 00:14:51.180
William Goldman--

00:14:51.180 --> 00:14:52.020
MARK KAUFMAN: Sorry.

00:14:52.020 --> 00:14:53.853
ALAN SEALES: --wrote
the original screenplay

00:14:53.853 --> 00:14:56.200
for the movie with Kathy Bates.

00:14:56.200 --> 00:14:58.736
So was it a kind of a
no-brainer to bring him back?

00:14:58.736 --> 00:15:00.360
Because he wrote the
screenplay, right?

00:15:00.360 --> 00:15:02.710
Or wrote the book for this.

00:15:02.710 --> 00:15:04.670
MARK KAUFMAN: He actually
comes from theater

00:15:04.670 --> 00:15:05.780
before he was in movies.

00:15:05.780 --> 00:15:08.040
Years ago, he
wrote, oh, my god, I

00:15:08.040 --> 00:15:11.110
think it was a Kander and
Ebb musical with his brother

00:15:11.110 --> 00:15:15.040
James, the happy time
in the late '50s.

00:15:15.040 --> 00:15:17.460
And he wrote a bunch
of books about theater.

00:15:17.460 --> 00:15:18.980
"Season" is an incredible book.

00:15:18.980 --> 00:15:22.840
If anybody hasn't read
it, it's unbelievable.

00:15:22.840 --> 00:15:24.100
So he was already hired.

00:15:24.100 --> 00:15:27.010
So it was just a matter of
do we continue with him?

00:15:27.010 --> 00:15:29.597
And I was in awe of him
in our first meeting,

00:15:29.597 --> 00:15:31.180
when he was telling
me all the things.

00:15:31.180 --> 00:15:32.780
And I have to say,
Will had already

00:15:32.780 --> 00:15:34.660
handled the projection stuff.

00:15:34.660 --> 00:15:37.540
So I didn't-- those were so
taken care of by the time I

00:15:37.540 --> 00:15:38.270
came on.

00:15:38.270 --> 00:15:41.470
So now, I got the
exciting stuff.

00:15:41.470 --> 00:15:43.145
And Bill, when I
remember-- William,

00:15:43.145 --> 00:15:46.377
sorry-- when we had our first
lunch, he was telling me this.

00:15:46.377 --> 00:15:47.960
And I was like a kid
in a candy store.

00:15:47.960 --> 00:15:49.730
I was like, oh, my
god, this is great.

00:15:49.730 --> 00:15:51.260
And so it just got me excited.

00:15:51.260 --> 00:15:53.430
And it was very easy to push it.

00:15:53.430 --> 00:15:57.095
ALAN SEALES: So were there any
budgetary or licensing hurdles

00:15:57.095 --> 00:15:57.770
to overcome?

00:15:57.770 --> 00:15:59.700
Or was it just like,
oh, cool, put it on.

00:15:59.700 --> 00:16:00.200
Let's do it?

00:16:00.200 --> 00:16:02.616
MARK KAUFMAN: Well, we shared
the rights with Castle Rock.

00:16:02.616 --> 00:16:03.800
It was actually their idea.

00:16:03.800 --> 00:16:05.720
Liz Glotzer and
Martin Shafer came

00:16:05.720 --> 00:16:08.810
to Warner Brothers, the
previous regime in theater

00:16:08.810 --> 00:16:10.170
to do the play.

00:16:10.170 --> 00:16:12.150
So they put it into development.

00:16:12.150 --> 00:16:13.802
And so we shared the
rights with them,

00:16:13.802 --> 00:16:15.510
so it was an obvious
thing going forward.

00:16:15.510 --> 00:16:17.112
But we also did an out-of-town.

00:16:17.112 --> 00:16:19.570
After we worked on it a little
bit, we went to Bucks County

00:16:19.570 --> 00:16:22.440
in Pennsylvania and did an
out-of-town tryout there.

00:16:22.440 --> 00:16:24.380
And the response was terrific.

00:16:24.380 --> 00:16:26.686
And we also knew-- it set
us on a path of, oh, these

00:16:26.686 --> 00:16:29.550
are the things we need
to do going forward.

00:16:29.550 --> 00:16:32.710
And I think we made
great progress.

00:16:32.710 --> 00:16:37.750
And you said, when Laurie
and Bruce got into the room

00:16:37.750 --> 00:16:41.954
with Will, I mean, they
sat there and talked

00:16:41.954 --> 00:16:42.620
for a long time.

00:16:42.620 --> 00:16:44.203
I was not part of
those conversations,

00:16:44.203 --> 00:16:47.100
because they really wanted
to just become that group.

00:16:47.100 --> 00:16:49.760
And what came out of it
was incredible and really

00:16:49.760 --> 00:16:53.834
just sort of pushed it further
down the path to Broadway.

00:16:53.834 --> 00:16:54.500
ALAN SEALES: So.

00:16:54.500 --> 00:16:58.642
I mean, WBTV has
done a lot of stuff.

00:16:58.642 --> 00:17:00.850
And even right now on
Broadway, "The Curious Incident

00:17:00.850 --> 00:17:02.350
of the Dog in the
Night-Time" is you guys.

00:17:02.350 --> 00:17:04.589
"Bridges of Madison
County," "Elf," the "Charlie

00:17:04.589 --> 00:17:06.964
and the Chocolate Factory"
musical that's in London right

00:17:06.964 --> 00:17:09.290
now, that you guys own.

00:17:09.290 --> 00:17:13.665
So compared to those--
you keep going on

00:17:13.665 --> 00:17:15.540
about "Misery," about
it was just like, yeah,

00:17:15.540 --> 00:17:15.960
it's a no-brainer.

00:17:15.960 --> 00:17:16.751
We do it, we do it.

00:17:16.751 --> 00:17:19.030
But compared to all of
those, are all of them

00:17:19.030 --> 00:17:20.160
that easy to greenlight?

00:17:20.160 --> 00:17:20.720
Or were you--

00:17:20.720 --> 00:17:21.040
MARK KAUFMAN: No.

00:17:21.040 --> 00:17:23.123
ALAN SEALES: --just coming
in here like, oh, yeah,

00:17:23.123 --> 00:17:24.939
Laurie Metcalf, genius, do it?

00:17:24.939 --> 00:17:27.105
MARK KAUFMAN: By the way,
that was an easy decision.

00:17:27.105 --> 00:17:28.700
Laurie Metcalf, genius, do it.

00:17:28.700 --> 00:17:29.950
Yes, that was easy.

00:17:29.950 --> 00:17:31.250
No, they're not all that easy.

00:17:31.250 --> 00:17:33.520
And some are good ideas,
and some are bad ideas,

00:17:33.520 --> 00:17:35.681
and some will get reworked.

00:17:35.681 --> 00:17:37.430
One of the things I
was very excited about

00:17:37.430 --> 00:17:39.512
was we do a lot of musicals.

00:17:39.512 --> 00:17:40.220
We did "Charlie."

00:17:40.220 --> 00:17:40.910
We did "Elf."

00:17:40.910 --> 00:17:42.535
We were involved with
"Madison County."

00:17:42.535 --> 00:17:45.205
The National Theatre came to
us for "Curious Incident."

00:17:45.205 --> 00:17:48.520
We jumped on that.

00:17:48.520 --> 00:17:50.970
We wanted to do something
else after "Misery."

00:17:50.970 --> 00:17:53.030
And we said, all
right, what movie

00:17:53.030 --> 00:17:56.287
lends itself to the same--
what is another movie that

00:17:56.287 --> 00:17:57.870
could be turned into
a play that feels

00:17:57.870 --> 00:17:58.974
like it's very theatrical?

00:17:58.974 --> 00:18:00.390
We're not just
doing it because we

00:18:00.390 --> 00:18:01.681
want to put something on stage.

00:18:01.681 --> 00:18:04.780
But it really feels like it
would take it a step forward

00:18:04.780 --> 00:18:06.650
by being on stage.

00:18:06.650 --> 00:18:08.450
And our next-- we just
announced last week,

00:18:08.450 --> 00:18:11.520
we're going to be doing "Dog Day
Afternoon," with Stephen Adly

00:18:11.520 --> 00:18:13.030
Guirgis adapting it.

00:18:13.030 --> 00:18:14.809
So it has to be the right idea.

00:18:14.809 --> 00:18:16.600
And I think that sounds
like the right idea

00:18:16.600 --> 00:18:17.808
for the way it was picked up.

00:18:17.808 --> 00:18:20.176
But we'll develop
it and we'll see.

00:18:20.176 --> 00:18:21.280
ALAN SEALES: Right.

00:18:21.280 --> 00:18:24.460
So Michael Friedman,
original music

00:18:24.460 --> 00:18:25.900
and original sound design.

00:18:25.900 --> 00:18:27.972
MICHAEL FRIEDMAN: No,
Darron West is the sound.

00:18:27.972 --> 00:18:28.930
ALAN SEALES: Oh, sorry.

00:18:28.930 --> 00:18:29.730
MICHAEL FRIEDMAN: He
would be very mad at me

00:18:29.730 --> 00:18:31.004
if I said I did the sound.

00:18:31.004 --> 00:18:31.670
ALAN SEALES: Oh.

00:18:31.670 --> 00:18:33.870
So, I mean, over and
over again, the lighting

00:18:33.870 --> 00:18:38.070
and the sound design are used
to indicate the passing of time,

00:18:38.070 --> 00:18:40.630
which I think the way that
you did it in the show

00:18:40.630 --> 00:18:41.440
was brilliant.

00:18:41.440 --> 00:18:43.900
Was that one of the
original slides,

00:18:43.900 --> 00:18:46.200
or it's just the stuff
that we shall not

00:18:46.200 --> 00:18:48.585
talk about that was slides?

00:18:48.585 --> 00:18:50.210
WILL FREARS: Oh,
everything was slides.

00:18:50.210 --> 00:18:51.690
I mean, the whole thing was.

00:18:51.690 --> 00:18:54.320
It was like there was a bed
and a projection machine.

00:18:54.320 --> 00:18:56.580
It was like, this is
a-- then he does this.

00:18:56.580 --> 00:18:58.038
Then he does-- and
it would-- you'd

00:18:58.038 --> 00:19:00.460
just be like-- I'm so--
like it was just all slides.

00:19:00.460 --> 00:19:02.680
It was like something
from the 19th century.

00:19:02.680 --> 00:19:03.180
Yeah.

00:19:03.180 --> 00:19:07.684
ALAN SEALES: Well, the sound
and the lighting-- yeah,

00:19:07.684 --> 00:19:09.100
I think it's
absolutely brilliant.

00:19:09.100 --> 00:19:10.558
And I was wondering,
because I knew

00:19:10.558 --> 00:19:13.586
that it was going to take
place over multiple days

00:19:13.586 --> 00:19:14.460
and going into weeks.

00:19:14.460 --> 00:19:17.360
And I was like, OK, first
off, there's one room.

00:19:17.360 --> 00:19:20.410
OK, it rotated to
start, but that's it.

00:19:20.410 --> 00:19:24.150
But how did you guys come
up with the overall concept

00:19:24.150 --> 00:19:26.540
for the underscoring
of the show,

00:19:26.540 --> 00:19:28.280
in addition to the lighting?

00:19:28.280 --> 00:19:31.047
You guys have things like
mobile gobos that move,

00:19:31.047 --> 00:19:33.380
that make it look like cars
are driving by, and whatnot.

00:19:33.380 --> 00:19:33.620
It' brilliant.

00:19:33.620 --> 00:19:35.260
MICHAEL FRIEDMAN: Well, David
Weiner, our lighting designer,

00:19:35.260 --> 00:19:36.950
is a genius at
that kind of thing.

00:19:36.950 --> 00:19:40.780
So it is, as you
say, the thing that's

00:19:40.780 --> 00:19:43.650
trickiest to do in theater
is to have time pass,

00:19:43.650 --> 00:19:45.640
because our show
is 90 minutes long.

00:19:45.640 --> 00:19:49.450
And a novel can
take a lot of time.

00:19:49.450 --> 00:19:52.320
So there are a lot of
scenes in the play.

00:19:52.320 --> 00:19:55.090
And so, the major thing that
we had to come up with first

00:19:55.090 --> 00:19:58.960
was how to tell the story of
now one night passes, now four

00:19:58.960 --> 00:19:59.990
nights pass.

00:19:59.990 --> 00:20:01.031
It's been snowing a lot.

00:20:01.031 --> 00:20:01.780
It's been raining.

00:20:01.780 --> 00:20:03.580
The seasons are changing.

00:20:03.580 --> 00:20:06.877
So we all worked--
it was actually

00:20:06.877 --> 00:20:07.960
one of the hardest things.

00:20:07.960 --> 00:20:09.501
I think, also on
the actors, in terms

00:20:09.501 --> 00:20:11.740
of exactly how long those
transitions should be,

00:20:11.740 --> 00:20:14.360
and where the play
needs to breathe,

00:20:14.360 --> 00:20:17.740
and where the play
needs to get tauter.

00:20:17.740 --> 00:20:20.860
So the music and sound
and lighting departments

00:20:20.860 --> 00:20:25.510
all spent long and tedious
hours building those.

00:20:25.510 --> 00:20:28.340
So I'm glad that you
liked them, because they

00:20:28.340 --> 00:20:29.300
were really hard to do.

00:20:29.300 --> 00:20:31.180
I've never seen,
actually, a show

00:20:31.180 --> 00:20:33.210
that exists quite
in that way in terms

00:20:33.210 --> 00:20:35.490
of telling a story about
time between the scenes.

00:20:35.490 --> 00:20:38.500
And I hope that it allows
the actors to then get

00:20:38.500 --> 00:20:40.090
the right lift-off
into each scene.

00:20:40.090 --> 00:20:42.860
ALAN SEALES: Yeah, I
found it extremely unique.

00:20:42.860 --> 00:20:44.446
Did you get tech
butt while you were

00:20:44.446 --> 00:20:45.570
sitting in the house, yeah?

00:20:45.570 --> 00:20:46.675
MICHAEL FRIEDMAN: We
got a lot of tech butt.

00:20:46.675 --> 00:20:47.140
ALAN SEALES: Yeah.

