ALAN SEALES: They were marveling
at our Googler at La Place,

00:20:53.597 --> 00:20:54.430
over here, the cafe.

00:20:54.430 --> 00:20:55.980
And I said, you've got to
watch out for the Googler 20.

00:20:55.980 --> 00:20:58.188
And they said, you've got
to watch out for tech butt.

00:20:58.188 --> 00:21:01.485
When you sit in the house all
the time, you get tech butt.

00:21:01.485 --> 00:21:03.110
WILL FREARS: Everyone's
very graciously

00:21:03.110 --> 00:21:09.220
put a bucket of candy on your
table, and you just look.

00:21:09.220 --> 00:21:12.100
ALAN SEALES: So how
is the composing

00:21:12.100 --> 00:21:16.170
of music for a play different
from the composition

00:21:16.170 --> 00:21:17.010
for a musical?

00:21:17.010 --> 00:21:17.750
MICHAEL FRIEDMAN:
Well, I'll admit

00:21:17.750 --> 00:21:20.250
that when I was telling people
I was working on "Misery,"

00:21:20.250 --> 00:21:23.552
there would be this weird
look of horror in their faces.

00:21:23.552 --> 00:21:25.260
And then I'd say, oh,
it's not a musical.

00:21:25.260 --> 00:21:26.898
And they'd go, oh,
that's a good idea.

00:21:26.898 --> 00:21:28.332
[LAUGHTER]

00:21:28.332 --> 00:21:34.070
So it was like, oh, you think
I'd write a really bad musical.

00:21:34.070 --> 00:21:37.420
But the trick of-- I
mean, horror movies

00:21:37.420 --> 00:21:39.930
rely on music hugely.

00:21:39.930 --> 00:21:42.330
And the tricky
part of "Misery" is

00:21:42.330 --> 00:21:43.670
the tone is really interesting.

00:21:43.670 --> 00:21:46.780
Because it's both scary,
and psychological,

00:21:46.780 --> 00:21:49.404
and suspenseful, and at
the same time, very funny.

00:21:49.404 --> 00:21:51.570
And the thing that music
can do better than anything

00:21:51.570 --> 00:21:53.710
is destroy humor.

00:21:53.710 --> 00:21:56.410
So my first job,
in a funny way, was

00:21:56.410 --> 00:21:59.740
to not kill what the actors
were doing beautifully,

00:21:59.740 --> 00:22:01.580
that as soon as you
add music under it,

00:22:01.580 --> 00:22:04.660
the audience is just sitting
there and nothing happens.

00:22:04.660 --> 00:22:07.225
So like Will said, getting
out of the actor's way

00:22:07.225 --> 00:22:08.470
is part of my job.

00:22:08.470 --> 00:22:12.390
But the fun part
was, horror allows

00:22:12.390 --> 00:22:15.590
you to do all sorts of
things-- bad taste things

00:22:15.590 --> 00:22:17.760
that I would never allow myself.

00:22:17.760 --> 00:22:20.610
Anyone who sees the show,
the final cue of the show

00:22:20.610 --> 00:22:24.370
is completely tasteless.

00:22:24.370 --> 00:22:30.560
But one of the fun things in
the show is that in the script,

00:22:30.560 --> 00:22:34.350
Annie's different mood
shifts are indicated by what

00:22:34.350 --> 00:22:36.720
Liberace she's listening to.

00:22:36.720 --> 00:22:40.450
So we started with the idea
of this Liberace piano.

00:22:40.450 --> 00:22:44.460
And I sort of let that start
infecting the other music.

00:22:44.460 --> 00:22:47.434
And then I just watched
"Psycho" over and over again.

00:22:47.434 --> 00:22:49.350
The score of "Psycho"
is the best horror movie

00:22:49.350 --> 00:22:50.020
score of all time.

00:22:50.020 --> 00:22:51.186
ALAN SEALES: Oh, yeah, yeah.

00:22:51.186 --> 00:22:52.670
Wow.

00:22:52.670 --> 00:22:56.360
So Leon Addison Brown,
you play Buster.

00:22:56.360 --> 00:22:57.980
I watched the show
last week, like I

00:22:57.980 --> 00:23:02.370
said, having not read the
book or watched the movie.

00:23:02.370 --> 00:23:04.990
And your-- gosh,
how do I-- I don't

00:23:04.990 --> 00:23:07.870
want to give any spoilers away.

00:23:07.870 --> 00:23:08.640
Your--

00:23:08.640 --> 00:23:09.470
MICHAEL FRIEDMAN:
Climactic moment.

00:23:09.470 --> 00:23:10.040
WILL FREARS: Climactic thing.

00:23:10.040 --> 00:23:11.456
ALAN SEALES: Your
climactic moment

00:23:11.456 --> 00:23:13.340
scared the everloving
shit out of me.

00:23:13.340 --> 00:23:15.660
And I was sitting
house-right, so I

00:23:15.660 --> 00:23:17.060
didn't see Laurie behind you.

00:23:17.060 --> 00:23:19.560
So I was completely-- I
didn't anticipate anything.

00:23:19.560 --> 00:23:20.760
And I was like, why is
he just standing there

00:23:20.760 --> 00:23:21.611
weirdly like that?

00:23:21.611 --> 00:23:22.110
OK.

00:23:22.110 --> 00:23:24.830
And then, boom, it
happened-- literally.

00:23:28.456 --> 00:23:30.300
Does your character--
I mean, you kind of

00:23:30.300 --> 00:23:32.405
come in and out of the
scene the whole time.

00:23:32.405 --> 00:23:34.280
Backstage, do you have
your own character arc

00:23:34.280 --> 00:23:36.420
that you're dealing
with with all of this?

00:23:36.420 --> 00:23:38.014
LEON ADDISON BROWN: I do.

00:23:38.014 --> 00:23:41.150
The difficult thing about
it is that I warm up,

00:23:41.150 --> 00:23:43.080
and then I have to wait.

00:23:43.080 --> 00:23:44.650
So by the time I
get on, I'm feeling

00:23:44.650 --> 00:23:46.536
like I need to warm up again.

00:23:46.536 --> 00:23:48.430
Then you're on for
that little short time,

00:23:48.430 --> 00:23:49.750
and then you wait again.

00:23:49.750 --> 00:23:53.550
So that part of it is
difficult, just staying in it.

00:23:53.550 --> 00:23:55.900
So I listen to the
whole show every night.

00:23:55.900 --> 00:23:59.560
I'm actually sometimes watching
the monitor when I'm not

00:23:59.560 --> 00:24:03.650
getting changed, just to
sort of keep myself in it,

00:24:03.650 --> 00:24:06.145
so I don't feel like I'm
starting from zero again.

00:24:06.145 --> 00:24:07.590
I watch the time pass.

00:24:07.590 --> 00:24:09.152
I watch the seasons change.

00:24:09.152 --> 00:24:10.420
I just do all that stuff.

00:24:10.420 --> 00:24:11.170
ALAN SEALES: Yeah.

00:24:11.170 --> 00:24:13.440
Oh, so, talk about
the seasons changing,

00:24:13.440 --> 00:24:15.190
I want to talk about
the set for a second.

00:24:15.190 --> 00:24:17.930
Because I believe that it's
just brilliantly designed.

00:24:17.930 --> 00:24:19.730
And I hope you can
comment on-- hopefully,

00:24:19.730 --> 00:24:20.896
you have some input on this.

00:24:20.896 --> 00:24:21.852
I want to praise you.

00:24:21.852 --> 00:24:22.977
WILL FREARS: I hope so too.

00:24:22.977 --> 00:24:24.480
ALAN SEALES: Yeah, yeah.

00:24:24.480 --> 00:24:27.380
The set, for those who will go
see it-- I'm not giving things

00:24:27.380 --> 00:24:29.838
away, because the first thing
that happens is the whole set

00:24:29.838 --> 00:24:34.250
turns-- there's four rooms
essentially in this house.

00:24:34.250 --> 00:24:37.580
So the whole stage
is a giant turntable,

00:24:37.580 --> 00:24:41.315
and you get to see at various
points each of the four rooms,

00:24:41.315 --> 00:24:43.050
or three rooms and outside.

00:24:43.050 --> 00:24:46.654
And part of the white walls move
to shift around for the actors,

00:24:46.654 --> 00:24:47.820
to give you guys more space.

00:24:47.820 --> 00:24:50.475
And I think it's
absolutely brilliant.

00:24:50.475 --> 00:24:53.070
How did that set come to be?

00:24:53.070 --> 00:24:55.549
It's very unique compared to
anything I've seen before.

00:24:55.549 --> 00:24:57.090
WILL FREARS: It came
to be, actually,

00:24:57.090 --> 00:25:00.650
in a very specific way, which
is that David Korins, who's not

00:25:00.650 --> 00:25:04.942
here, and I were having a
sort of early conversation

00:25:04.942 --> 00:25:06.400
about what we wanted
it to be like.

00:25:06.400 --> 00:25:08.099
And we felt very strongly.

00:25:08.099 --> 00:25:10.140
I mean, it all comes back
to the same idea, which

00:25:10.140 --> 00:25:11.730
is making room for the actors.

00:25:14.490 --> 00:25:17.270
We wanted to put Annie's
house on the stage.

00:25:17.270 --> 00:25:19.330
We didn't want to have
an idea about a house,

00:25:19.330 --> 00:25:23.645
or some comment from
outside, or an opinion.

00:25:23.645 --> 00:25:26.730
We wanted to give her the
place where she lived,

00:25:26.730 --> 00:25:30.510
that we could reveal more story
that way, that we could find--

00:25:30.510 --> 00:25:33.190
and that we wanted-- and this
was a word we used endlessly--

00:25:33.190 --> 00:25:34.810
we wanted claustrophobia.

00:25:34.810 --> 00:25:37.640
We wanted a kind of super
claustrophobic realism.

00:25:37.640 --> 00:25:41.390
And so anytime you
break the plane,

00:25:41.390 --> 00:25:42.876
you allow the
audience to breathe.

00:25:42.876 --> 00:25:44.750
And that's why we don't
have an intermission.

00:25:44.750 --> 00:25:47.547
It's why there's no blackouts.

00:25:47.547 --> 00:25:49.130
There aren't meant
to be rest moments.

00:25:49.130 --> 00:25:54.950
And so the idea was let's
put her whole house on stage.

00:25:54.950 --> 00:25:57.610
And then once we go--
when the house moves,

00:25:57.610 --> 00:26:00.169
we want to follow-- we
want to be in real time.

00:26:00.169 --> 00:26:02.210
It is, again, the thing
Michael was saying about,

00:26:02.210 --> 00:26:03.418
like we go back all the time.

00:26:03.418 --> 00:26:05.530
And when the house
is in motion, we

00:26:05.530 --> 00:26:07.300
want it to be really
in motion, happening

00:26:07.300 --> 00:26:08.830
in front of your eyes.

00:26:08.830 --> 00:26:11.280
And so the idea was to
just try and jam it all.

00:26:11.280 --> 00:26:12.750
I remember David
calling me one day

00:26:12.750 --> 00:26:15.190
and saying-- or me calling him
and saying, how's it going?

00:26:15.190 --> 00:26:17.340
He said, I'm almost
being a good set

00:26:17.340 --> 00:26:20.760
designer, because I've almost
got it all on the turntable.

00:26:20.760 --> 00:26:22.550
And before that,
we would have bits

00:26:22.550 --> 00:26:25.170
like, oh, we can't get the
stairs on the turntable.

00:26:25.170 --> 00:26:26.890
And we just kept compressing it.

00:26:26.890 --> 00:26:29.370
And every time we
compressed it, it

00:26:29.370 --> 00:26:31.070
got more claustrophobic
and more real.

00:26:31.070 --> 00:26:33.121
And we just kept pushing
it further and further

00:26:33.121 --> 00:26:33.870
in that direction.

00:26:33.870 --> 00:26:37.170
And then you and
David would talk about

00:26:37.170 --> 00:26:40.010
what was in the house,
so that everything

00:26:40.010 --> 00:26:44.900
has texture and detail and
is informed by the story,

00:26:44.900 --> 00:26:48.440
not just comment from outside.

00:26:48.440 --> 00:26:50.470
And also, that I
was always taken

00:26:50.470 --> 00:26:54.200
by the idea of a cabin in the
woods and a kind of "Hansel

00:26:54.200 --> 00:26:56.350
and Gretel" kind
of feeling of like,

00:26:56.350 --> 00:26:58.957
that I thought it was important
to have the desolation,

00:26:58.957 --> 00:27:00.540
to really feel that
this was happening

00:27:00.540 --> 00:27:03.180
in the middle of nowhere.

00:27:03.180 --> 00:27:04.660
So that was how we did it.

00:27:04.660 --> 00:27:07.240
And we just kept
going with that idea

00:27:07.240 --> 00:27:09.768
instead of pushing it
further and further.

00:27:09.768 --> 00:27:11.070
ALAN SEALES: Wow.

00:27:11.070 --> 00:27:12.160
So is it interesting?

00:27:12.160 --> 00:27:14.490
Laurie, have you ever
worked with a set like this?

00:27:14.490 --> 00:27:16.440
You basically don't get
any time to breathe.

00:27:16.440 --> 00:27:19.240
You and Bruce are on stage
pretty much the whole time.

00:27:19.240 --> 00:27:23.444
As he said, it's real time,
including the passage of time.

00:27:23.444 --> 00:27:25.860
LAURIE METCALF: We do have
some moments of tag team, where

00:27:25.860 --> 00:27:29.220
Bruce is on stage
alone and figuring out

00:27:29.220 --> 00:27:32.000
how he's going to get out of
the room with whatever key

00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:33.750
he can manufacture, and stuff.

00:27:33.750 --> 00:27:37.216
But when he's doing
that, I'm backstage

00:27:37.216 --> 00:27:38.590
getting ready for
something else.

00:27:38.590 --> 00:27:42.350
We don't really leave it.

00:27:42.350 --> 00:27:44.189
We do get literally
stuck on that thing.

00:27:44.189 --> 00:27:45.730
ALAN SEALES: Is
there a big crew back

00:27:45.730 --> 00:27:47.396
there that's all of
a sudden just coming

00:27:47.396 --> 00:27:50.640
to dump props and everything,
and take the snow off the side?

00:27:50.640 --> 00:27:54.274
LAURIE METCALF: Our tech
week was hellish, because--

00:27:54.274 --> 00:27:55.440
WILL FREARS: It was awesome.

00:27:55.440 --> 00:27:58.770
LAURIE METCALF: --as you're
timing the light cues

00:27:58.770 --> 00:28:01.910
with the music and the
revolve, then Bruce

00:28:01.910 --> 00:28:05.020
is timing how fast he's
going in a wheelchair,

00:28:05.020 --> 00:28:07.100
and the lights are
shift, and the music--

00:28:07.100 --> 00:28:10.790
it's all shifting as he
passes through the doorway.

00:28:10.790 --> 00:28:14.100
And then you reveal the hallway.

00:28:14.100 --> 00:28:16.940
And your audience is seeing
it for the first time.

00:28:16.940 --> 00:28:21.750
But it was so
intricate, and we just

00:28:21.750 --> 00:28:24.720
had to time it over and
over and over again.

00:28:24.720 --> 00:28:28.190
MICHAEL FRIEDMAN: You were
very patient with us--

00:28:28.190 --> 00:28:30.597
MARK KAUFMAN: --as we
tortured you with music.

00:28:30.597 --> 00:28:31.930
ALAN SEALES: Has the turntable--

00:28:31.930 --> 00:28:34.150
LAURIE METCALF: 25 scenes,
and each one has a--

00:28:34.150 --> 00:28:34.740
MICHAEL FRIEDMAN: Oh, don't ask.

00:28:34.740 --> 00:28:35.881
Don't ask that question.

00:28:35.881 --> 00:28:36.630
ALAN SEALES: Yeah.

00:28:36.630 --> 00:28:39.307
MICHAEL FRIEDMAN: No, and
don't ask, That's a curse.

00:28:39.307 --> 00:28:40.640
LAURIE METCALF: What did he say?

00:28:40.640 --> 00:28:41.670
Oh, "Has it."

00:28:41.670 --> 00:28:43.370
ALAN SEALES: Has the turntable--

00:28:43.370 --> 00:28:43.690
MICHAEL FRIEDMAN: No.

00:28:43.690 --> 00:28:44.210
WILL FREARS: No.

00:28:44.210 --> 00:28:44.490
ALAN SEALES: Good

00:28:44.490 --> 00:28:45.070
MICHAEL FRIEDMAN:
No, don't say ever.

00:28:45.070 --> 00:28:45.970
Please don't say it.

00:28:45.970 --> 00:28:48.057
MARK KAUFMAN: Never broken.

00:28:48.057 --> 00:28:49.390
ALAN SEALES: What would happen--

00:28:49.390 --> 00:28:51.515
LAURIE METCALF: But there
was a million props also.

00:28:51.515 --> 00:28:53.060
The handling of
all that had to get

00:28:53.060 --> 00:28:55.654
swept up into this tech week.

00:28:55.654 --> 00:28:57.320
MICHAEL FRIEDMAN: We
had a bad few days,

00:28:57.320 --> 00:29:00.042
where in spring, there
was some snow on the roof.

00:29:00.042 --> 00:29:02.000
ALAN SEALES: People just
forgot to take it off?

00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:03.708
MICHAEL FRIEDMAN: No,
no one knew how to.

00:29:03.708 --> 00:29:06.220
There was no moment in
which it could be taken off.

00:29:06.220 --> 00:29:07.914
Somehow they
heroically take it off.

00:29:07.914 --> 00:29:09.330
ALAN SEALES: It's
all very subtle.

00:29:09.330 --> 00:29:09.970
I love it.

00:29:09.970 --> 00:29:14.810
Because you see the flowers
get put on the porch, and then

00:29:14.810 --> 00:29:17.720
