00:31:01.440 --> 00:31:04.340
that Kathy's wonderful
performance would stick

00:31:04.340 --> 00:31:06.770
in my head in a really bad way.

00:31:06.770 --> 00:31:09.720
But I did go back to the
book, which I had also

00:31:09.720 --> 00:31:11.000
read when it came out.

00:31:11.000 --> 00:31:15.352
And to revisit that
was really helpful.

00:31:15.352 --> 00:31:20.230
It's a lot about Paul
Sheldon's interior life

00:31:20.230 --> 00:31:25.680
and the torture that he's
having to take from this woman.

00:31:25.680 --> 00:31:28.250
The book is also
very, very theatrical.

00:31:28.250 --> 00:31:32.210
There's a lot of
really-- even more

00:31:32.210 --> 00:31:34.820
gruesome things happen
in the book that

00:31:34.820 --> 00:31:37.040
were chosen to be in the movie.

00:31:37.040 --> 00:31:40.150
And then ours is
a hybrid of both.

00:31:40.150 --> 00:31:42.470
Because we have things
that are from the book,

00:31:42.470 --> 00:31:45.212
that weren't in the
movie, and vice versa.

00:31:45.212 --> 00:31:54.710
So there were so
many options, I felt,

00:31:54.710 --> 00:31:58.000
going into "Misery"
the play, that it

00:31:58.000 --> 00:32:02.065
was daunting in that way.

00:32:05.820 --> 00:32:08.297
But I like that it's a blend.

00:32:08.297 --> 00:32:10.880
WILL FREARS: One of the things
that we realized when we did it

00:32:10.880 --> 00:32:16.320
in Pennsylvania was that he's
stuck on stage the whole time.

00:32:16.320 --> 00:32:19.500
He's stuck in this room,
and so you have to--

00:32:19.500 --> 00:32:21.820
and this was what's
wonderful about the movie.

00:32:21.820 --> 00:32:24.520
And because I am a
coward, I'd never

00:32:24.520 --> 00:32:28.100
watched the movie because the
trailer scared me too much.

00:32:28.100 --> 00:32:31.080
So I didn't watch it until
I sat in the NYU hospital

00:32:31.080 --> 00:32:34.150
room with my
two-day-old on my chest.

00:32:34.150 --> 00:32:37.150
But the movie is
brilliant in what it takes

00:32:37.150 --> 00:32:40.840
from-- the book is spectacular.

00:32:40.840 --> 00:32:42.540
And it's all in
Paul's voice, and it's

00:32:42.540 --> 00:32:44.050
all Paul's point of view.

00:32:44.050 --> 00:32:46.650
And what Bill Goldman
does in the movie that's

00:32:46.650 --> 00:32:48.890
so brilliant, as a human,
he finds this new way

00:32:48.890 --> 00:32:52.709
of looking at Annie, and
going out into Annie's world.

00:32:52.709 --> 00:32:53.500
And it's wonderful.

00:32:53.500 --> 00:32:55.166
But then when you
went back to the play,

00:32:55.166 --> 00:32:57.620
you were like, we
don't have a camera.

00:32:57.620 --> 00:33:01.050
This can only happen between
the two of them in this room.

00:33:01.050 --> 00:33:03.089
And so everything sort
of got-- the stuff

00:33:03.089 --> 00:33:05.380
we took from the book, the
stuff we got from the movie,

00:33:05.380 --> 00:33:07.400
it all had to be
recompressed into

00:33:07.400 --> 00:33:10.249
like, how does this happen
between the two of them?

00:33:10.249 --> 00:33:11.790
How can this happen
in the space that

00:33:11.790 --> 00:33:15.010
exists in their conversation
or in what they're not saying?

00:33:15.010 --> 00:33:18.680
And I think that was the big--
that everything from both

00:33:18.680 --> 00:33:21.720
the mediums had to be
channeled back into like,

00:33:21.720 --> 00:33:23.840
can this take place
between the two of them

00:33:23.840 --> 00:33:26.930
in the space that exists
between the two of them?

00:33:26.930 --> 00:33:30.140
And I think that was our
main-- I went back to the movie

00:33:30.140 --> 00:33:32.147
at the end.

00:33:32.147 --> 00:33:33.730
Once it was all
worked out in my head,

00:33:33.730 --> 00:33:35.790
and I would be sort
of stuck in places.

00:33:35.790 --> 00:33:38.073
And then I felt like I
had a secure enough grip

00:33:38.073 --> 00:33:40.572
of the story I was telling,
that then I would go back and be

00:33:40.572 --> 00:33:41.610
like, how did they do it?

00:33:41.610 --> 00:33:42.750
Because I might just steal that.

00:33:42.750 --> 00:33:43.530
So I would use it.

00:33:43.530 --> 00:33:45.030
Once I knew what I
was doing, I felt

00:33:45.030 --> 00:33:48.450
liberated to steal from very,
very clever people in a way

00:33:48.450 --> 00:33:51.920
that, earlier on, I would
have felt, as Laurie says,

00:33:51.920 --> 00:33:54.865
like I would have just ended up
trying to mimic a lot of stuff

00:33:54.865 --> 00:33:56.490
from the movie, rather
than at the end,

00:33:56.490 --> 00:33:57.906
being able to go
back and be like,

00:33:57.906 --> 00:33:59.350
oh, oh, I'll have a bit of that.

00:33:59.350 --> 00:34:01.324
That's clever.

00:34:01.324 --> 00:34:03.365
And so that was it, but
I haven't seen the movie.

00:34:03.365 --> 00:34:05.180
So I can't remember the last
time I watched the whole movie.

00:34:05.180 --> 00:34:07.263
I would watch and be like
how do they do that bit?

00:34:07.263 --> 00:34:09.792
And I would go back and watch
that over and over again.

00:34:09.792 --> 00:34:11.250
LEON ADDISON BROWN:
I saw the movie

00:34:11.250 --> 00:34:13.870
when it came out many years ago.

00:34:13.870 --> 00:34:17.840
And reading the book,
I was a little shocked

00:34:17.840 --> 00:34:19.940
that Buster is actually
a composite, I think,

00:34:19.940 --> 00:34:22.889
of different police
officers that show up.

00:34:22.889 --> 00:34:28.530
And so I didn't have to-- I was
hoping that I could get stuff

00:34:28.530 --> 00:34:29.889
from the book for him.

00:34:29.889 --> 00:34:35.360
But I had to go find my own
cop book which was amazing.

00:34:40.060 --> 00:34:42.830
Mr. Goldman must have
sat down and talked

00:34:42.830 --> 00:34:44.010
to detectives, or something.

00:34:44.010 --> 00:34:45.760
Because some of the
answers that she gives

00:34:45.760 --> 00:34:49.600
are all these cues and
clues in it about, hmm,

00:34:49.600 --> 00:34:50.920
there's something here.

00:34:50.920 --> 00:34:53.139
There's something
here in every scene.

00:34:53.139 --> 00:34:56.775
And I was like, thank you.

00:34:56.775 --> 00:34:57.650
MARK KAUFMAN: Can I--

00:34:57.650 --> 00:34:57.970
ALAN SEALES: Yeah, go ahead.

00:34:57.970 --> 00:34:58.940
MARK KAUFMAN: --I just want
to add one thing, though.

00:34:58.940 --> 00:35:01.189
One of the things I think
we've done very successfully

00:35:01.189 --> 00:35:04.360
is when we sought out to
do this in the first place,

00:35:04.360 --> 00:35:05.410
we have the book.

00:35:05.410 --> 00:35:06.220
You have the movie.

00:35:06.220 --> 00:35:08.280
And we wanted to create
something that was its own.

00:35:08.280 --> 00:35:09.821
So yes, it pulls
from the other ones.

00:35:09.821 --> 00:35:12.390
But it has things that are
also unique to the play that

00:35:12.390 --> 00:35:14.530
aren't in either the
book or the movie.

00:35:14.530 --> 00:35:18.150
So we set out to not create
a souvenir of either,

00:35:18.150 --> 00:35:20.100
but a companion piece,
the same way the movie

00:35:20.100 --> 00:35:21.475
is a companion
piece of the book.

00:35:21.475 --> 00:35:23.570
And I think that's what
we've done successfully.

00:35:23.570 --> 00:35:27.220
MICHAEL FRIEDMAN: And one
more thing, which is there's

00:35:27.220 --> 00:35:31.162
one iconic moment in the
movie that is not in the book,

00:35:31.162 --> 00:35:33.370
or it's very different in
the book, which is probably

00:35:33.370 --> 00:35:36.170
the most famous iconic moment
in the movie-- no spoilers.

00:35:36.170 --> 00:35:38.150
But we had to get that right.

00:35:38.150 --> 00:35:39.140
WILL FREARS: Yes.

00:35:39.140 --> 00:35:39.620
MICHAEL FRIEDMAN: We knew.

00:35:39.620 --> 00:35:41.661
And we didn't quite get
it right in Pennsylvania,

00:35:41.661 --> 00:35:43.540
and the audience
didn't quite forgive us

00:35:43.540 --> 00:35:44.600
for not getting it right.

00:35:44.600 --> 00:35:47.020
And no, and it was the big
thing we had to get right.

00:35:47.020 --> 00:35:51.241
And it was pretty exciting when
the actors, and the designers,

00:35:51.241 --> 00:35:52.990
and the director, and
all the stage hands,

00:35:52.990 --> 00:35:54.770
when everyone
finally came together

00:35:54.770 --> 00:35:58.380
to make that moment work was
really probably when we knew.

00:35:58.380 --> 00:36:01.480
The audience reaction suddenly
was like, oh, we gave you

00:36:01.480 --> 00:36:02.585
what you were waiting for.

00:36:02.585 --> 00:36:04.880
And that's also a
very wonderful thing

00:36:04.880 --> 00:36:06.960
to be able to do
for an audience.

00:36:06.960 --> 00:36:08.620
ALAN SEALES: Right.

00:36:08.620 --> 00:36:13.030
Were you influenced at all
by the music in the movie?

00:36:13.030 --> 00:36:16.270
MICHAEL FRIEDMAN: I quickly
started watching it.

00:36:16.270 --> 00:36:19.089
And Marc Shaiman wrote
a really good score.

00:36:19.089 --> 00:36:20.130
It's Marc Shaiman, right?

00:36:20.130 --> 00:36:20.965
MARK KAUFMAN: Marc Shaiman,
the "Hairspray" composer.

00:36:20.965 --> 00:36:22.100
MICHAEL FRIEDMAN: Marc
Shaiman, who did "Hairspray,

00:36:22.100 --> 00:36:24.070
wrote a really good score.

00:36:24.070 --> 00:36:25.960
It's actually
strangely unhelpful

00:36:25.960 --> 00:36:28.852
because movies are so
different from plays.

00:36:28.852 --> 00:36:30.310
So it was nice to
start watching it

00:36:30.310 --> 00:36:31.643
and go, oh, I couldn't use that.

00:36:31.643 --> 00:36:32.836
None of this would work.

00:36:32.836 --> 00:36:34.230
ALAN SEALES: [CHUCKLES]

00:36:34.230 --> 00:36:34.960
MICHAEL FRIEDMAN:
Let's start over.

00:36:34.960 --> 00:36:35.260
ALAN SEALES: Yeah.

00:36:35.260 --> 00:36:35.760
Yeah.

00:36:35.760 --> 00:36:37.530
Question over here?

00:36:37.530 --> 00:36:38.314
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:36:38.314 --> 00:36:40.230
Mark, you mentioned that
"Misery" spoke to you

00:36:40.230 --> 00:36:43.700
because of the theatricalism
you felt inherent in the piece.

00:36:43.700 --> 00:36:46.020
I was wondering, in general,
when Warner Brothers

00:36:46.020 --> 00:36:49.100
is choosing shows to adapt for
the theater, what you look for.

00:36:49.100 --> 00:36:50.822
And also, more to
the point, if there

00:36:50.822 --> 00:36:52.530
is going to be a
"Goonies-- The Musical"?

00:36:52.530 --> 00:36:53.780
[LAUGHTER]

00:36:53.780 --> 00:36:54.530
MARK KAUFMAN: Wow.

00:36:54.530 --> 00:36:57.660
ALAN SEALES: Good question.

00:36:57.660 --> 00:36:59.960
MARK KAUFMAN: Well, again,
there are different ways

00:36:59.960 --> 00:37:01.970
to do theater.

00:37:01.970 --> 00:37:02.860
There's the musical.

00:37:02.860 --> 00:37:04.030
There's the play.

00:37:04.030 --> 00:37:05.100
There are reviews.

00:37:05.100 --> 00:37:08.410
There are now immersive theater,
like there are pieces where

00:37:08.410 --> 00:37:09.940
you follow the actors around.

00:37:09.940 --> 00:37:11.895
So as far as what
we look for, it's

00:37:11.895 --> 00:37:13.740
just something that
feels like it naturally

00:37:13.740 --> 00:37:16.970
adapts to the stage.

00:37:16.970 --> 00:37:18.690
It has to have a theatricality.

00:37:18.690 --> 00:37:21.790
It has to feel like
you could transform it

00:37:21.790 --> 00:37:22.757
into something else.

00:37:22.757 --> 00:37:25.090
It feels like, to me, though,
when we're putting theater

00:37:25.090 --> 00:37:26.780
together, it's the next step.

00:37:26.780 --> 00:37:29.260
It can't just be, oh,
let's take the movie

00:37:29.260 --> 00:37:30.680
and just do it on stage.

00:37:30.680 --> 00:37:32.390
Like I said before
about "Misery,"

00:37:32.390 --> 00:37:35.299
it can't be the
souvenir of the piece.

00:37:35.299 --> 00:37:36.590
it has to be a companion piece.

00:37:36.590 --> 00:37:39.747
And what can you add to the
piece by putting it on stage?

00:37:39.747 --> 00:37:41.580
I think with "Elf," we
were very successful.

00:37:41.580 --> 00:37:44.670
And "Hairspray" was
incredibly successful

00:37:44.670 --> 00:37:49.142
because the John Waters movie
and the musical on Broadway

00:37:49.142 --> 00:37:50.600
were two complete
different things,

00:37:50.600 --> 00:37:55.480
as I feel the Adam Shankman
movie was another step forward.

00:37:55.480 --> 00:37:59.301
And so I guess my
long answer to that

00:37:59.301 --> 00:38:01.800
is that we look for something
that feels like it organically

00:38:01.800 --> 00:38:06.040
feels like it belongs on stage,
where there is relationship,

00:38:06.040 --> 00:38:11.450
some emotional arc, some sort
of reason to have it sing.

00:38:11.450 --> 00:38:12.400
We're doing "Dave."

00:38:12.400 --> 00:38:13.945
We're doing "Seventeen Again."

00:38:13.945 --> 00:38:17.900
These pieces feel like
they belong on stage.

00:38:17.900 --> 00:38:22.260
And I guess time will tell
whether we're right or not.

00:38:22.260 --> 00:38:24.850
But we're trying.

00:38:24.850 --> 00:38:27.470
ALAN SEALES: You mentioned
the audience a second ago.

00:38:27.470 --> 00:38:29.330
The audience, they finally were
like, yes, you gave it to us.

00:38:29.330 --> 00:38:30.320
This is what we want.

00:38:30.320 --> 00:38:34.420
Is the overall audience
reaction this time--

00:38:34.420 --> 00:38:36.300
I guess, first off,
first question, how

00:38:36.300 --> 00:38:39.050
is it different here in New
York versus at Bucks County?

00:38:39.050 --> 00:38:41.070
WILL FREARS: I think
we're different now.

00:38:41.070 --> 00:38:45.960
I think part of it is
that in Bucks County,

00:38:45.960 --> 00:38:48.050
we were testing it out.

00:38:48.050 --> 00:38:52.670
And I think, I look
back, we were much more--

00:38:52.670 --> 00:38:55.947
we worked in a way that I I'm
glad we've moved away from.

00:38:55.947 --> 00:38:58.030
We did much more like we're
going to be scary now.

00:38:58.030 --> 00:39:00.228
Like the thunder was
endlessly the loudest thunder

00:39:00.228 --> 00:39:01.760
you'd ever heard.

00:39:01.760 --> 00:39:04.270
And the lightning was
like really "lightningy."

00:39:04.270 --> 00:39:05.020
And I think that--

00:39:05.020 --> 00:39:05.700
ALAN SEALES: Lightningy.

00:39:05.700 --> 00:39:06.700
WILL FREARS: Lightningy.

00:39:06.700 --> 00:39:09.520
And I think that what we
did was we found a way,

00:39:09.520 --> 00:39:12.430
and so in a way, we didn't
yet trust what we had.

00:39:12.430 --> 00:39:14.230
I mean, we were
right not to, which

00:39:14.230 --> 00:39:17.500
is that we didn't trust it,
so we handed over everything

00:39:17.500 --> 00:39:18.480
to see what worked.

00:39:18.480 --> 00:39:20.521
And I think that what we
came out of Pennsylvania

00:39:20.521 --> 00:39:24.130
with was a much clearer sense
of the story we were telling.

00:39:24.130 --> 00:39:27.070
I mean, it was the most-- I'd
like to do it with anything

00:39:27.070 --> 00:39:28.690
I direct, which is do it once.

00:39:28.690 --> 00:39:31.200
Figure out where you've
gotten off track,

00:39:31.200 --> 00:39:34.630
and then go back and
do it again better.

00:39:34.630 --> 00:39:39.440
To have had the opportunity to
learn from it was a real treat,

00:39:39.440 --> 00:39:42.020
so thank you, Mark.

00:39:42.020 --> 00:39:44.791
And I think we went back and
went like, oh, now we know

00:39:44.791 --> 00:39:46.040
the story we're going to tell.

00:39:46.040 --> 00:39:48.670
Now we can be more interesting.

00:39:48.670 --> 00:39:50.780
We can be bolder.

00:39:50.780 --> 00:39:53.220
We can be stranger because we
know what it is we're doing.

00:39:53.220 --> 00:39:55.910
And we trust it more, so
we don't have to just make

00:39:55.910 --> 00:39:57.355
the thunder really loud.

00:39:57.355 --> 00:39:58.980
I mean, we do in
places still, but it's

00:39:58.980 --> 00:40:03.610
less-- we stopped tap
dancing quite so fast.

00:40:03.610 --> 00:40:06.990
And I think that's what we
came into rehearsal with.

00:40:06.990 --> 00:40:09.990
And then I think Laurie and
Bruce, once they showed up,

00:40:09.990 --> 00:40:14.385
brought such extra-- I think
that the actors in Pennsylvania

00:40:14.385 --> 00:40:16.510
were very much that doing
what we needed them to do

00:40:16.510 --> 00:40:17.676
to see what the play worked.

00:40:17.676 --> 00:40:20.130
And Laurie and Bruce
bring such originality,

00:40:20.130 --> 00:40:22.690
and eccentricity,
and strangeness to it

00:40:22.690 --> 00:40:26.310
that it's become a kind
of-- the one in Pennsylvania

00:40:26.310 --> 00:40:28.090
was really like,
here's the movie.

00:40:28.090 --> 00:40:29.580
We're kind of figuring it out.

00:40:29.580 --> 00:40:32.470
And here I think
we have a thing.

00:40:32.470 --> 00:40:34.750
We've pulled the script apart.

00:40:34.750 --> 00:40:36.850
Laurie and Bruce give
these sort of very strange,

00:40:36.850 --> 00:40:39.170
very interesting, very
human performances.

00:40:39.170 --> 00:40:43.430
The design leads in
more interesting places.

00:40:43.430 --> 00:40:46.080
So it has a confidence
now, I think,

00:40:46.080 --> 00:40:47.850
that it didn't have
in Bucks County.

00:40:47.850 --> 00:40:49.892
In Bucks County, it
really was sort of--

00:40:49.892 --> 00:40:51.100
ALAN SEALES: Experimentation.

00:40:51.100 --> 00:40:52.640
WILL FREARS: Yeah, or
not experimentive enough,

00:40:52.640 --> 00:40:54.710
where they're like, hey,
hey, do you like it?

00:40:54.710 --> 00:40:56.342
Do you like it?

00:40:56.342 --> 00:40:57.800
MARK KAUFMAN: The
set evolved also.

00:40:57.800 --> 00:40:59.150
ALAN SEALES: I was
going to ask about that.

00:40:59.150 --> 00:40:59.720
MICHAEL FRIEDMAN: A lot.

00:40:59.720 --> 00:41:00.560
Yeah.

00:41:00.560 --> 00:41:01.360
ALAN SEALES: Was it
the original house

00:41:01.360 --> 00:41:02.812
with the turntable there too?

00:41:02.812 --> 00:41:03.770
MARK KAUFMAN: No.

00:41:03.770 --> 00:41:05.470
WILL FREARS: The room
was quite similar.

00:41:05.470 --> 00:41:08.590
The door was in the same place,
but I think that was about it.

00:41:08.590 --> 00:41:11.160
No, no, you spend your
life trying to figure out

00:41:11.160 --> 00:41:12.190
where the door goes.

00:41:12.190 --> 00:41:13.370
Once you figure out
where the door goes,

00:41:13.370 --> 00:41:15.110
pretty much everything
else makes sense.

00:41:15.110 --> 00:41:19.000
But the door-- no,
how to you move?

00:41:19.000 --> 00:41:20.170
She comes in.

00:41:20.170 --> 00:41:20.900
He's in bed.

00:41:20.900 --> 00:41:23.441
Nobody's moving, so you've got
to figure out the relationship

00:41:23.441 --> 00:41:25.100
between bed and door.

00:41:25.100 --> 00:41:27.036
It's like 80% percent
of the blocking.

00:41:29.580 --> 00:41:31.405
Desperate to get
away from the door.

00:41:31.405 --> 00:41:32.675
ALAN SEALES: Yeah.

00:41:32.675 --> 00:41:34.439
Yeah, question over here?

00:41:34.439 --> 00:41:34.980
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:41:34.980 --> 00:41:35.729
I have a question.

00:41:37.995 --> 00:41:40.370
I guess when you first got
together in the room and said,

00:41:40.370 --> 00:41:42.687
this is how we are going to
scare audiences and really

00:41:42.687 --> 00:41:44.770
bring them in, how do you
think being in a theater

00:41:44.770 --> 00:41:47.430
and seeing this
performance live is

00:41:47.430 --> 00:41:50.510
different from being scared--
somebody sitting in a movie

00:41:50.510 --> 00:41:55.350
theater and being brought into
a film versus being on stage

00:41:55.350 --> 00:41:58.109
and seeing it?

00:41:58.109 --> 00:41:59.650
MICHAEL FRIEDMAN:
Well, it's actually

00:41:59.650 --> 00:42:01.080
happening in front of you.

00:42:01.080 --> 00:42:03.030
I mean, which I know
is the obvious answer,

00:42:03.030 --> 00:42:05.330
but it's also true.

00:42:05.330 --> 00:42:06.259
These are real people.

00:42:06.259 --> 00:42:08.050
I mean, that's my
experience watching this.

00:42:08.050 --> 00:42:09.772
These are real people.

00:42:09.772 --> 00:42:10.980
WILL FREARS: And real bodies.

00:42:10.980 --> 00:42:13.146
MICHAEL FRIEDMAN: Yeah,
real people and real bodies.

00:42:13.146 --> 00:42:16.640
And a few times, wait,
that can't be a real body.

00:42:16.640 --> 00:42:18.250
But that experience
which is that this

00:42:18.250 --> 00:42:21.580
is happening in front of you,
and they are actually doing it.

00:42:21.580 --> 00:42:23.730
I mean there's a fight
at the end, where

00:42:23.730 --> 00:42:26.180
Bruce and Laurie go at
each other in a rather

00:42:26.180 --> 00:42:28.270
frightening way.

00:42:28.270 --> 00:42:30.600
And a fight on stage is a
completely different thing

00:42:30.600 --> 00:42:33.456
than a fight in a movie.

00:42:33.456 --> 00:42:34.830
There's a little
bit of distance.

00:42:34.830 --> 00:42:37.288
As exciting as the movie is,
it's a different and, I think,

00:42:37.288 --> 00:42:38.730
a more distanced experience.

00:42:38.730 --> 00:42:40.220
WILL FREARS: And I think that
the pleasure of being scared

00:42:40.220 --> 00:42:41.680
in a movie so much
is the edit, that you

00:42:41.680 --> 00:42:43.100
cut, you change
the angle, or you

00:42:43.100 --> 00:42:44.391
play a thing that wasn't there.

00:42:44.391 --> 00:42:49.660
And I think what we're going
for is that it builds up

00:42:49.660 --> 00:42:52.320
to this incredibly kind of
climactic violent moment,

00:42:52.320 --> 00:42:55.870
and to train the audience
to believe everything.

00:42:55.870 --> 00:42:58.714
And what you do is
you keep not cutting.

00:42:58.714 --> 00:42:59.880
You keep not going to black.

00:42:59.880 --> 00:43:02.430
You keep not giving
a kind of [GASP]

00:43:02.430 --> 00:43:05.134
so that it all-- there's a
sort of cumulative effect

00:43:05.134 --> 00:43:06.800
of a different--
almost like you haven't

00:43:06.800 --> 00:43:08.662
been allowed to stop looking.

00:43:08.662 --> 00:43:10.620
Laurie is there the whole
time and you're going

00:43:10.620 --> 00:43:12.130
to have to keep looking at her.

00:43:12.130 --> 00:43:13.230
We're not cutting away.

00:43:13.230 --> 00:43:16.230
We're not giving you anything
outside of this room.

00:43:16.230 --> 00:43:19.052
I mean, the movie cuts
its passage of time.

00:43:19.052 --> 00:43:21.260
It cuts to the mountains
and you watch the snow melt.

00:43:21.260 --> 00:43:24.594
But you cut to the mountains,
and you breathe for a second.

00:43:24.594 --> 00:43:25.760
We don't have any mountains.

00:43:25.760 --> 00:43:26.420
We've only got--

00:43:26.420 --> 00:43:28.780
LAURIE METCALF: We also don't
have the benefit of close-ups.

00:43:28.780 --> 00:43:29.488
WILL FREARS: Yes.

00:43:29.488 --> 00:43:31.160
LAURIE METCALF: So
that's a big one.

00:43:31.160 --> 00:43:35.142
You can get a lot of mileage
out of a really good close-up,

00:43:35.142 --> 00:43:37.656
and we can't do that.

00:43:37.656 --> 00:43:38.570
WILL FREARS: No.

00:43:38.570 --> 00:43:42.360
ALAN SEALES: There's a lot of
realistic blood as well, which

00:43:42.360 --> 00:43:44.600
speaking as an audience
member not involved

00:43:44.600 --> 00:43:45.400
in the production--

00:43:45.400 --> 00:43:47.025
MICHAEL FRIEDMAN: We
have a blood room.

00:43:47.025 --> 00:43:48.579
ALAN SEALES: Do you, really?

00:43:48.579 --> 00:43:49.870
WILL FREARS: Don't go in there.

00:43:49.870 --> 00:43:53.140
ALAN SEALES: Buster just
goes in and coats himself.

00:43:53.140 --> 00:43:59.790
Yeah, that was the difference
for me versus in a movie,

00:43:59.790 --> 00:44:00.290
I guess.

00:44:00.290 --> 00:44:02.010
Like I'm looking
at it, and I know

00:44:02.010 --> 00:44:03.890
it's not real anyway,
because it's a movie.

00:44:03.890 --> 00:44:07.835
But of course, in theater,
I know it's not real.

00:44:07.835 --> 00:44:10.610
People aren't getting hurt every
night, over and over again--

00:44:10.610 --> 00:44:13.060
most of the time.

00:44:13.060 --> 00:44:16.540
But for me, like you said,
seeing real people involved

00:44:16.540 --> 00:44:18.420
with this, and seeing
all of a sudden,

00:44:18.420 --> 00:44:22.580
Buster's little climactic scene,
and the noise, and the boom,

00:44:22.580 --> 00:44:24.380
it's-- all right.

00:44:24.380 --> 00:44:26.119
I don't-- sorry.

00:44:26.119 --> 00:44:27.660
WILL FREARS: No, I
just wanted to ask

00:44:27.660 --> 00:44:31.420
you, Laurie, as the
person who is scary,

00:44:31.420 --> 00:44:34.130
how much do you-- like I
have this idea about what

00:44:34.130 --> 00:44:35.310
we're doing to scare people.

00:44:35.310 --> 00:44:39.302
But you are the agent
of scariness on stage.

00:44:39.302 --> 00:44:41.010
How much do you think
about that as you--

00:44:41.010 --> 00:44:44.320
LAURIE METCALF: I don't
think about it at all.

00:44:44.320 --> 00:44:45.355
Am I scary in it?

00:44:45.355 --> 00:44:45.980
WILL FREARS: Terrifying, yes.

00:44:45.980 --> 00:44:47.960
ALAN SEALES: Oh, yeah, yeah,
by the end of it, yeah.

00:44:47.960 --> 00:44:48.835
WILL FREARS: Oh, and
like really scary.

00:44:48.835 --> 00:44:51.001
LAURIE METCALF: Well,
hopefully, the reason for that

00:44:51.001 --> 00:44:52.859
is that she's just
unpredictable, right?

00:44:52.859 --> 00:44:53.650
ALAN SEALES: Right.

00:44:53.650 --> 00:44:55.608
LAURIE METCALF: So you
don't know what-- first,

00:44:55.608 --> 00:44:58.111
you start to get a hint of
what she might be capable of.

00:44:58.111 --> 00:44:58.860
ALAN SEALES: Yeah.

00:44:58.860 --> 00:45:00.340
LAURIE METCALF: So I
guess it's the-- yeah,

00:45:00.340 --> 00:45:01.570
it's the unpredictability.

00:45:01.570 --> 00:45:06.690
So I don't have to try
and actually scare people.

00:45:06.690 --> 00:45:11.190
That's not where that's
coming from, right?

00:45:11.190 --> 00:45:12.517
The fear is coming from.

00:45:12.517 --> 00:45:13.350
Because it can't be.

00:45:13.350 --> 00:45:17.240
Nobody can-- you look
this big on the stage.

00:45:17.240 --> 00:45:18.917
No, that can't be scary.

00:45:18.917 --> 00:45:20.860
WILL FREARS: I mean, it is.

00:45:20.860 --> 00:45:22.610
LAURIE METCALF: But I
guess it's just her.

00:45:22.610 --> 00:45:28.090
Sometimes the rage that's in
her, I guess, might be scary.

00:45:28.090 --> 00:45:31.964
My kids don't think so,
but audiences might.

00:45:31.964 --> 00:45:33.130
ALAN SEALES: We totally did.

00:45:33.130 --> 00:45:35.397
And for me, like you said,
it's the unpredictability,

00:45:35.397 --> 00:45:37.480
especially when it comes
to causing physical harm.

00:45:39.842 --> 00:45:41.300
That's what pushed
me over the edge

00:45:41.300 --> 00:45:43.236
is that, OK, she's
a little nuts.

00:45:43.236 --> 00:45:44.360
She says some weird things.

00:45:44.360 --> 00:45:47.280
And then all of a sudden,
like about halfway through.

00:45:47.280 --> 00:45:49.440
it escalates very, very quickly.

00:45:49.440 --> 00:45:53.092
And for me, watching it,
the character of Annie,

00:45:53.092 --> 00:45:54.800
it was like just
another day in the park.

00:45:54.800 --> 00:45:56.210
Like, oh, well, this is
what's going to happen,

00:45:56.210 --> 00:45:57.400
and boom, there it happened.

00:45:57.400 --> 00:45:59.650
And while the rest of us--
the audience-- is cringing.

00:45:59.650 --> 00:46:02.470
And there are people all
around me in the audience

00:46:02.470 --> 00:46:03.994
talking as if it's
a horror movie.

00:46:03.994 --> 00:46:05.035
They're like, oh, my god.

00:46:05.035 --> 00:46:05.850
Is she going to go inside?

00:46:05.850 --> 00:46:06.400
What's going to happen?

00:46:06.400 --> 00:46:06.950
It's going to hit her like that?

00:46:06.950 --> 00:46:07.280
LAURIE METCALF: Really?

00:46:07.280 --> 00:46:09.840
ALAN SEALES: Oh, yeah, there's
people whispering behind me,

00:46:09.840 --> 00:46:10.800
like watch this.

00:46:10.800 --> 00:46:12.320
What's going on?

00:46:12.320 --> 00:46:14.780
And I realized that
people are literally

00:46:14.780 --> 00:46:16.780
watching it like they're
watching a horror film.

00:46:16.780 --> 00:46:18.320
MARK KAUFMAN: The
sound of 1,200 people

00:46:18.320 --> 00:46:19.300
in the Longacre screaming--

00:46:19.300 --> 00:46:19.630
WILL FREARS: The Broadhurst.

00:46:19.630 --> 00:46:20.850
MICHAEL FRIEDMAN:
--is like the coolest.

00:46:20.850 --> 00:46:22.350
The Broadhurst--
don't mention that.

00:46:22.350 --> 00:46:23.660
(LOUDLY) Broadhurst!

00:46:23.660 --> 00:46:28.079
Screaming is like the awesomest
sound I've ever heard.

00:46:28.079 --> 00:46:29.620
ALAN SEALES: Yeah,
it was incredible.

00:46:29.620 --> 00:46:30.310
LAURIE METCALF: And laughing.

00:46:30.310 --> 00:46:31.220
MICHAEL FRIEDMAN: And laughing.

00:46:31.220 --> 00:46:33.095
ALAN SEALES: Yeah, there
were the funny parts

00:46:33.095 --> 00:46:35.550
in there too, which was a
wonderful juxtaposition.

00:46:35.550 --> 00:46:36.900
Man, your character, you just--

00:46:36.900 --> 00:46:39.200
LAURIE METCALF: That's why
we call it a "thrilomedy."

00:46:39.200 --> 00:46:40.490
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:40.490 --> 00:46:42.656
ALAN SEALES: It's like "The
Martian" being a comedy.

00:46:42.656 --> 00:46:44.153
LAURIE METCALF: Yeah.

00:46:44.153 --> 00:46:45.736
ALAN SEALES: Yeah,
question over here?

00:46:45.736 --> 00:46:46.550
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:46:46.550 --> 00:46:49.710
I was actually going to
ask about what you just

00:46:49.710 --> 00:46:50.510
touched upon.

00:46:50.510 --> 00:46:54.470
But when I watched the
movie, I didn't find it

00:46:54.470 --> 00:46:57.140
very funny or pleasant at all.

00:46:57.140 --> 00:47:01.036
It was a very unsettling movie.

00:47:01.036 --> 00:47:03.030
And then when I saw
it in the theater,

00:47:03.030 --> 00:47:05.277
I saw it during previews,
so it might have changed.

00:47:05.277 --> 00:47:10.487
But the scene everyone keeps
avoiding talking about--

00:47:10.487 --> 00:47:11.401
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:11.401 --> 00:47:11.860
LEON ADDISON BROWN:
The one where

00:47:11.860 --> 00:47:13.290
Buster falls from the roof?

00:47:13.290 --> 00:47:15.607
Or the one where--

00:47:15.607 --> 00:47:16.940
ALAN SEALES: The bungee jumping.

00:47:16.940 --> 00:47:18.510
AUDIENCE: --finally figures out.

00:47:18.510 --> 00:47:21.280
And then, you know.

00:47:21.280 --> 00:47:24.300
When I saw that, there were
a lot of shocked screams

00:47:24.300 --> 00:47:27.206
but then this wave of laughter.

00:47:27.206 --> 00:47:32.420
And I just thought that was
like a really-- I did not expect

00:47:32.420 --> 00:47:34.096
the play to be like that.

00:47:34.096 --> 00:47:37.890
But do you think that's
a necessary property

00:47:37.890 --> 00:47:39.710
of doing horror in a theater?

00:47:39.710 --> 00:47:41.980
Or is that something
you were going for?

00:47:41.980 --> 00:47:44.960
Or a combination of both?

00:47:44.960 --> 00:47:47.740
MARK KAUFMAN: I think we were
all surprised about-- I mean,

00:47:47.740 --> 00:47:50.410
from when we started previews,
the audience's response

00:47:50.410 --> 00:47:51.050
was terrific.

00:47:51.050 --> 00:47:54.500
And I think what we were--
I, at least, personally,

00:47:54.500 --> 00:47:56.330
what I was most
surprised about was

00:47:56.330 --> 00:47:59.000
about how much
humor was in there,

00:47:59.000 --> 00:48:00.500
and how people got
on for the ride.

00:48:00.500 --> 00:48:03.770
And I wasn't sure whether it was
because they knew the character

00:48:03.770 --> 00:48:06.710
from the book, or whether
they-- Laurie's performance is

00:48:06.710 --> 00:48:09.410
extraordinary.

00:48:09.410 --> 00:48:13.010
So whether they love her,
or hate her, or whatever,

00:48:13.010 --> 00:48:14.200
they follow her.

00:48:14.200 --> 00:48:15.790
And they feel sympathy for her.

00:48:15.790 --> 00:48:18.520
And she really elicits
this amazing reaction

00:48:18.520 --> 00:48:19.270
from the audience.

00:48:19.270 --> 00:48:22.410
And I think some of it is
release, and some of it

00:48:22.410 --> 00:48:24.300
is just because
they feel for her.

00:48:24.300 --> 00:48:27.076
But it's genuine laughter,
which is pretty extraordinary.

00:48:27.076 --> 00:48:28.575
MICHAEL FRIEDMAN:
I think sometimes,

00:48:28.575 --> 00:48:32.790
though, in the theater, when
there's a moment of horror,

00:48:32.790 --> 00:48:35.852
the audience has the
reaction and then realizes

00:48:35.852 --> 00:48:37.060
they've all had the reaction.

00:48:37.060 --> 00:48:39.710
And that part of the
humor that comes out of it

00:48:39.710 --> 00:48:41.440
is what you said, the
release, which is,

00:48:41.440 --> 00:48:42.740
we all just screamed together.

00:48:42.740 --> 00:48:43.690
That was really scary.

00:48:43.690 --> 00:48:46.640
And then they kind of
laugh, and it's almost

00:48:46.640 --> 00:48:48.140
an automatic nervous response.

00:48:48.140 --> 00:48:51.180
It's fun to watch the
audience in those moments

00:48:51.180 --> 00:48:53.104
and try to figure
out the psychology.

00:48:53.104 --> 00:48:54.020
ALAN SEALES: Oh, yeah.

00:48:54.020 --> 00:48:56.940
It was after moments like
that that, and traditionally

00:48:56.940 --> 00:48:59.340
through theater, you don't
talk through it, and whatnot.

00:48:59.340 --> 00:49:02.069
But then as every moment
just stairstepped,

00:49:02.069 --> 00:49:03.610
and the tension kept
building, people

00:49:03.610 --> 00:49:05.955
were just having
whole conversations.

00:49:05.955 --> 00:49:08.080
This one guy was sitting
behind me completely about

00:49:08.080 --> 00:49:09.450
to just lose his mind
because he didn't know

00:49:09.450 --> 00:49:11.040
what you were going to do next.

00:49:11.040 --> 00:49:16.102
And it was exciting for me to
experience all these people

00:49:16.102 --> 00:49:19.380
around me getting as
nervous and as excited

00:49:19.380 --> 00:49:21.520
as I know that you
guys intend them to be.

00:49:21.520 --> 00:49:24.800
So job accomplished,
job well done.

00:49:24.800 --> 00:49:26.310
So thank you very much.

